{{refimprove|date=May 2014}}
'''Environmental hormones''' are chemical compounds that resembles [[endocrine]] [[hormone]]s. They may be either of natural origin, such as [[phytoestrogen]]s, or of synthetic origin.  These compounds are able to activate the same endocrine [[Receptor_(biochemistry)|receptors]] as their natural counterparts and can thus disrupt hormonal activity. <ref>{{cite journal|last=Danzo |first=B. J. |title=The effects of environmental hormones on reproduction |journal=CMLS, Cell. Mol. Life Sci. |date=15 June 1998 |volume=54 |pages=1249–1264 |url=http://download.springer.com/static/pdf/29/art%253A10.1007%252Fs000180050251.pdf?auth66=1400153647_47d5c8a823e57a7cdc4db96fb0b2c6fc&ext=.pdf |accessdate=13 May 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514025525/http://download.springer.com/static/pdf/29/art%253A10.1007%252Fs000180050251.pdf?auth66=1400153647_47d5c8a823e57a7cdc4db96fb0b2c6fc&ext=.pdf |archivedate=14 May 2014 |df= }}</ref>

