{{coord|40|12|37|N|46|48|33|E|display=title}} {{refimprove|date=June 2017}} {{Infobox settlement <!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions --> | name = Martakert | native_name = Մարտակերտ | type = [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh|Province]] | image_map = NKR locator Mardakert.png | seat_type = Capital | seat = [[Aghdara (town)|Martakert]] | leader_title = Governor | leader_name = Vladik Khachatryan | area_total_km2 = 1,795 | area_water_percent = Negligible | area_rank = [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh#By_area|Ranked 4th]] | population_total = 20,185 | population_footnotes = <ref name="census">[http://census.stat-nkr.am/nkr/1-4.pdf Census] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306035735/http://census.stat-nkr.am/nkr/1-4.pdf |date=2009-03-06 }}</ref> | population_as_of = 2013 | population_rank = [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh#By_population|Ranked 3rd]] | population_density_km2 = auto | postal_code_type = [[Nagorno-Karabakh postal codes|Postal code]] | postal_code = | area_code_type = [[FIPS 10-4]] | area_code = | iso_code = | website = [http://gov.nkr.am/hy/regions/details/48/ Martakert Province] }} '''Martakert Province''' ({{lang-hy|Մարտակերտ}}) is a [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh|province]] of the ''de facto'' [[Republic of Artsakh]]. The Republic has [[Political status of Nagorno-Karabakh|limited international recognition]]. It is ''de jure'' part of the Republic of [[Azerbaijan]]. The population is mainly Armenian. Martakert Province has 43 communities of which 1 is considered urban and 42 are rural.
== Cultural sites== The [[Gandzasar monastery]], the [[Yeghishe Arakyal Monastery]] and the 17th century Armenian monastery [[Yerits Mankants]] are located in this province. The [[Vankasar Monastery]] is just outside the town of [[Aghdara (town)|Martakert]]. The archaeological site of the town of [[Tigranakert of Artsakh|Tigranakert]] is also located here. Thought to have been founded in the 2nd-1st century B.C, it has been undergoing excavation since 2005. Some of the walls of the city, with Hellenistic-style towers, as well as Armenian basilica dating to fifth to seventh centuries have been uncovered.
